2025-12-12 | Minimum Window Subsequence

	Question
Given two strings s1 and s2,  
return the smallest substring in s1 such that s2 is a subsequence of that substring.  
If no such substring exists, return an empty string.

	Approach
1.	Use a **two-pointer greedy approach**.
2.	Iterate over s1 with index `i`, and track progress in s2 using index `j`.
3.	Whenever characters match, increment `j`.
4.	When `j` reaches the length of s2:
	-	We have found a valid window ending at index `i`.
5.	Now **shrink the window from the right to left**:
	-	Move backward to find the smallest possible start index
		while still keeping s2 as a subsequence.
6.	Record this window if it is smaller than previously found ones.
7.	Reset pointers and continue scanning for the next possible window.
8.	Time Complexity:
	-	O(n Ã— m) in worst case
		where n = length of s1, m = length of s2.
9.	Space Complexity:
	-	O(1)

	Solution

class Solution {
public:
    string minWindow(string s1, string s2) {
        int n = s1.size();
        int m = s2.size();

        int minLen = INT_MAX;
        int start = -1;

        int i = 0;
        while (i < n) {
            int j = 0;
            // Step 1: find subsequence match
            while (i < n) {
                if (s1[i] == s2[j]) {
                    j++;
                    if (j == m) break;
                }
                i++;
            }

            if (j < m) break; // no more valid windows

            // Step 2: shrink window from right to left
            int end = i;
            j = m - 1;
            while (i >= 0) {
                if (s1[i] == s2[j]) {
                    j--;
                    if (j < 0) break;
                }
                i--;
            }

            int currLen = end - i + 1;
            if (currLen < minLen) {
                minLen = currLen;
                start = i;
            }

            // move i to next possible start
            i = i + 1;
        }

        return (start == -1) ? "" : s1.substr(start, minLen);
    }
};
